<PageLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <script slot="head" type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="page-hero page-hero--neutral">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:800px;">
      <span class="eyebrow">DIY Garage Cabinets</span>
      <h1 class="page-h1">{title}</h1>
      <p style="font-family:var(--sans); color:var(--muted); font-size:17px; line-height:1.6; margin-top:20px; max-width:640px;">Skip the contractor. Skip the cam locks. Klovo's patent-pending GlideLock system turns garage cabinet installation into an afternoon project — no experience required, almost no tools, and a finished result that looks like a professional built it.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--cream">
    <div class="container" style="max-width:800px;">
      <article class="prose-klovo">

        <h2>Why DIY Garage Cabinets Make Sense in 2026</h2>
        <p>Garage storage has historically fallen into one of two camps: cheap big-box shelving that looks like an afterthought, or custom-installed cabinetry that costs as much as a kitchen remodel. For most homeowners, neither option is right.</p>
        <p>Custom installation typically runs $5,000–$15,000+ depending on garage size, materials, and your local labor market. It requires coordinating schedules, living without a usable garage for days, and paying for labor that has nothing to do with the quality of the finished product. Big-box steel shelving, meanwhile, rarely exceeds 100–150 lbs of shelf capacity, ships with hardware that strips on the third use, and still leaves your garage looking like a warehouse.</p>
        <p>The DIY cabinet market has matured significantly. Modular RTA systems now use the same materials as professional cabinet lines. The bottleneck was always assembly time — traditional cam-lock RTA can take 45–90 minutes per cabinet, which adds up fast. Klovo's GlideLock system collapses that to 2–3 minutes per cabinet box, making a full wall installation genuinely achievable in a single afternoon.</p>
        <p>Add the 500 lb per cabinet weight capacity, kitchen-grade TFL finish, and Georgia USA manufacturing, and the value equation is hard to argue with.</p>

        <h2>How GlideLock Makes It Possible</h2>
        <p>The patent-pending GlideLock connector system is the engineering core of every Klovo cabinet. Traditional RTA cabinets rely on cam locks — small rotating fasteners tightened with an Allen key that must be driven into a precisely positioned hole. Miss the hole by a millimeter, and the cam lock strips or the panel won't seat flat. After an hour of wrestling with 15 cam locks per cabinet, most homeowners are questioning their life choices.</p>
        <p>GlideLock works differently. Each panel is precision-drilled with connector slots that only fit together in one orientation. Slide the panel into position, press, and the connector locks by hand. There's a physical click. You know it's right. No tools required for this step.</p>
        <p>The only tool required in the entire build process is a screwdriver or drill for the four screws that secure the back panel runners at the end of each cabinet. That's it. "No cam locks, no Allen wrenches, no guesswork" isn't a marketing phrase — it's a literal description of what's not in the box.</p>
        <p>For wall mounting, you'll need a level and a stud finder (standard tools most homeowners already own). The mounting process is straightforward: find studs, mark positions, attach the wall rail that comes in the set, and hang cabinets onto the rail. The rail system lets you slide cabinets into final position before locking them down — no commitment to a hole location until you're sure it's right.</p>
        <p>For a complete walkthrough, visit the <a href="/assembly/">Klovo Assembly Guide</a>.</p>

        <h2>Who Is a DIY Garage Cabinet Project Right For?</h2>
        <p>If you've ever assembled flat-pack furniture — a bookshelf, a bed frame, a desk — you have more than enough experience to install Klovo cabinets. The GlideLock system is deliberately error-proof: panels fit in only one configuration, so there's no spatial reasoning required about which cam lock goes in which direction.</p>
        <p>Klovo is appropriate for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>First-time DIY builders</strong> who want a professional result without contractor experience</li>
          <li><strong>Renovation enthusiasts</strong> who enjoy weekend projects and want quality materials</li>
          <li><strong>Homeowners who move</strong> — Klovo disassembles and reassembles, unlike custom builds</li>
          <li><strong>Renters with landlord approval</strong> — wall mounts are standard anchors, fully reversible</li>
          <li><strong>Garage gym builders</strong> — the 500 lb per cabinet capacity handles weight plates and equipment storage</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The project is not appropriate for anyone who needs cabinetry installed and inspected for a real estate transaction within 24 hours, or for anyone without a standard drill for the wall-mounting phase.</p>

        <h2>Sizing Guide: Which Klovo Set Fits Your Garage</h2>
        <p>Measure your available wall in linear feet before ordering. Leave 6 inches of clearance on each side if you're not going wall-to-wall, and account for garage door swing arc if cabinets are near the door opening.</p>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Garage Size</th>
              <th>Recommended Set</th>
              <th>Set Width</th>
              <th>Typical Use</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>1-car garage</td>
              <td>6-foot sets</td>
              <td>6 ft</td>
              <td>One full wall with a short workbench section</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2-car garage (one wall)</td>
              <td>8-foot or 10-foot sets</td>
              <td>8–10 ft</td>
              <td>Full wall coverage, workbench + upper storage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2-car garage (two walls)</td>
              <td>Two 8-foot sets or one 16-foot</td>
              <td>16 ft total</td>
              <td>L-shaped or opposing-wall configuration</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>3-car / oversized garage</td>
              <td>16–20 foot sets</td>
              <td>16–20 ft</td>
              <td>Floor-to-ceiling coverage, workshop + storage</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Laundry / utility room</td>
              <td>6–8 foot sets</td>
              <td>6–8 ft</td>
              <td>Overhead cabinets above washer/dryer</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Basement storage</td>
              <td>Custom build</td>
              <td>Any</td>
              <td>Individual base + tall cabinets for flexible layout</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>All Klovo sets are modular: you can start with a 6-foot set and expand to 20+ feet later without replacing existing cabinets. Individual cabinets, door kits, and worktops are sold separately for custom layouts.</p>
        <p><a href="/sets/">Browse All Sets and Configurations &rarr;</a></p>

        <h2>DIY vs. Hiring a Contractor: A Real Comparison</h2>

        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Factor</th>
              <th>Klovo DIY</th>
